{"author":{"id":"977fec8a59c245f25e0e700fa290ef50836c624572869487e9e47fedc85061ee"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445085484,"nonce":"rp8y0RNCjz2SKS5K6/3FxN1zZ1Q=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkxMzg5OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148913899"},"message":"\u003e Tools can not register new datatypes. Tools can change metadata (to some degree) of an already existing datatype. All feature count tools are producing files that are tab separated, I think this is the most common denominator :).\n\nWell, I see the problems in my proposition now. Yet, that would be an interesting approach.\n\n\u003e Are we talking about a new file type here? Shouldn't be a file type as strictly defined as possible?\n\u003e What do you gain from a new file type that has no defined number of columns, no definition of header/comments over the already existing tabular format?\n\nI don't really know how to express this well, I'll just called it a datatype, even if that may not be a datatype in the most commonly used sense. The idea would be to have a datatype that can have a set of metadata associated to it. This metadata would include the number of samples (1 or more), the feature that is being counted (genes, exons, whatever is currently in the first column produced by count tools) and the count-data itself (per sample and feature).\nThe purpose of this is that tool wrappers that produce counts would set this new datatypes as output format and assign columns and rows of their tabular output data to the correct metadata.\nThen the datatype would also take care of the conversion, so that tools that need a header-line in their input receive the correct header line, and tools that need multiple input files (one per sample) would receive this as input.\nLet me know if you think this is nonsense (honesty appreciated!). I'll be pretty busy the next weeks, but I could keep this in my inbox.","files":null}]}